Arkansas' Katrina Nesby had a career
night Monday in the 76-66 victory against Texas
Christian.
article.headline: Nesby goes 8-for-10 shooting in scoring 19 points
article.linkText: Nesby helps No. 16 Arkansas get past No. 19 TCU
article.story:
FAYETTEVILLE, Ark. (AP) -- Arkansas' Katrina Nesby had a career
night Monday in the 76-66 victory against Texas
Christian.

	   The 6-foot-4 guard scored 19 points on 8-for-10 shooting from the
field and 3-for-6 from the line.

	   TCU (1-1) didn't expect Nesby to be a sharpshooter for Arkansas
(2-0; No. 16 ESPN/USA Today; No. 17 Associated Press), Nesby said, adding that she acted as a decoy in distracting TCU (No. 19 ESPN/USA Today).

	   ''They focused on India (Lewis) shooting and Shameka (Christon),
and I just came out of nowhere,'' Nesby said.

	   Lewis scored 26 points, 11 from free throws in the second half.
She finished the game 14-for-16 from the line and 5-for-11 from the
field in 40 minutes of play.

	   Tiffany Evans started the scoring in the first quarter with a
3-pointer for TCU. Then Arkansas went on a nine-point scoring run
midway through the quarter, starting with a layup by Nesby, to
bring the Lady Razorbacks from behind, 10-9.

	   ''We came out sluggish,'' Lewis said. ''I think once we got into
our full-court pressure, we kind of feed off that because that's
more our style, and we love to score off of either turnovers or
steals, and that's what got us into our little run.''

	   Tracy Wynn ended the Arkansas run with a layup and
narrowed the margin for TCU, but Arkansas remained ahead 19-13.

	   Going into the half, Arkansas led 37-33, but seven free throws
within three minutes helped the Lady Frogs recapture the lead.

	   Lewis answered with a 3-pointer and a pair of free throws to tie
the game at 42. In all, Lewis took six trips to the line in the
second half. Rochelle Vaughn was fouled and added a duo of her own
to put the Lady Razorbacks in the lead, 44-42.

	   TCU's Kim Ortega was fouled and nailed two from the line to tie
Arkansas at 44, but a shot in front of the basket from Shanna
Harmon toppled the lead back in Arkansas' favor.

	   Harmon added another 2-pointer to create some breathing space,
but a couple more trips to the line allowed TCU to take a two-point lead with little more than eight minutes left
in the game.

	   Two trips to the line for Lewis regained the lead for Arkansas,
and a behind-the-back pass from Dana Cherry to Nesby in front of
Arkansas' basket put the Lady Razorbacks up, 58-53, to secured the
lead for the rest of the game.

	   Although Nesby and Lewis had some good plays, having several of
the freshmen fill in when the others became tired was the key to
winning the game, Arkansas coach Gary Blair said.

	   ''We made three turnovers in ... the first four possessions,''
Blair said. ''These were our older kids making these mistakes and
sometimes you need a wake-up call.''
